# The Consensus Pipeline: How Advocacy Documents Become Clinical Evidence

*Part of the adversarial research series. Toolkit and evidence archive at the links below.*

-----

Three documents have functioned as the load-bearing evidence for “settled science” arguments about gender-affirming care in American legal briefs, legislative testimony, and clinical guidelines. They are cited as independent sources. They are not independent. Each one cites the others, and all three trace back to the same evidentiary base — a set of heterogeneous, mostly uncontrolled clinical follow-up studies that a 2018 Cornell literature review coded by direction of finding rather than evidence quality.

This paper maps the pipeline, audits each document against the toolkit’s construct validity and citation network prompts, and names the failure mode directly: **citation laundering operationalized as health policy.**

The pipeline continued operating after the Cass Review, the NICE systematic reviews, and the Scandinavian health technology assessments applied quality-weighted methodology to the same literature and reached substantially different conclusions. That continuation — documented with specific dates — is the ratchet signature.

-----

## The Narrowest Defensible Claim

Before the audit: what the evidence actually supports.

Most patients in clinical follow-up samples who completed gender transition treatment and remained in contact with clinical services reported positive outcomes on self-report measures.

That is a real finding. It is not “robust international consensus” adequate to settle contested policy questions about population-level guidelines, access for minors, or medical necessity determinations. The gap between those two things is the paper.

