## Document One: HRC “Get the Facts”

The HRC is an advocacy organization. “Get the Facts” is advocacy output. That categorization matters when the document is cited as independent scientific summary.

The evidentiary structure: claims are supported by links to studies selected for positive findings, with no acknowledgment of contrary evidence or methodological limits. The puberty blocker “fully reversible” claim is stated as settled fact; the contested evidence on bone density, brain development windows, and fertility does not appear. The “every major medical organization supports” framing is used as a substitute for evidentiary argument.

One study the HRC document cites as positive evidence — Tordoff et al. (2022), *JAMA Network Open* — received a formal journal correction in July 2022 for data errors in supplementary tables. Analysis of the study’s own reported data shows depression prevalence was 57% at baseline and 56% at 12-month follow-up in the hormone group — no statistically significant improvement. The Dutch studies underpinning much of the clinical protocol have been subject to peer-reviewed methodological critique identifying selection of only highest-functioning cases, faulty measurement of gender dysphoria resolution, and inability to separate effects of simultaneous psychotherapy, hormones, and surgery (Abbruzzese, Levine & Mason, 2023, *Journal of Sex & Marital Therapy*).

None of these appear in the HRC document, which was updated in **January 2025** — nine months after the final Cass Report — without referencing it.

> **Verdict: Fatal construct validity failure for its policy use.** Advocacy material cited as science is a category error, not a methodological weakness.

