## Document Two: Cornell “What We Know” (2018) — The Hub

The Cornell document is the academic anchor of the pipeline. It carries institutional credibility. It has not been updated since 2018. Its methodology does not support the “robust international consensus” it exports.

### Why 93% Is Not a Meta-Analytic Finding

The 93% positive rate is not a pooled effect size. Not a weighted estimate. Not a GRADE assessment. Not a risk-of-bias-adjusted synthesis. Not a durability finding.

It is a directional vote count across heterogeneous studies.

The five-part failure:

**Direction ≠ quality.** No formal risk-of-bias tool is applied. A retrospective satisfaction survey of 28 patients with no control group counts identically to a prospective cohort study.

A common objection here: the ethical difficulty of RCTs in this population — withholding treatment from those who seek it — makes high-tier evidence unavailable through constraint, not negligence. That constraint is real. But the ethical difficulty of producing rigorous evidence does not license presenting the resulting low-certainty evidence as robust consensus adequate for population-level policy. The appropriate response to an evidence base constrained by ethical limits is epistemic humility — not confidence inflation in the summary language.

**Direction ≠ clinical significance.** A tiny short-term improvement in self-reported satisfaction is not the same as large durable improvement across objective and subjective outcomes. Cornell treats them equivalently.

**Direction ≠ durability.** A study showing early gains that do not persist at 5-year follow-up is counted as positive, because the short-term direction is positive.

**Direction ≠ attribution.** Many studies cannot isolate what produced any observed improvement: social transition, psychotherapy, hormones, surgery, family support, or clinical attention. Cornell treats “transition” as a clean intervention when the underlying studies measure bundles.

**Direction ≠ population-level policy evidence.** Direction-of-finding in self-selected clinical follow-up samples cannot support claims about what happens to the full range of people who seek treatment — including those denied, those who detransition, and those who disengage.

### Additional Methodological Omissions

- **No transparent search protocol.** No database list, no search terms, no formal inclusion/exclusion criteria. The 55-study set cannot be independently replicated or audited.
- **Outcome non-commensurability.** Satisfaction, dysphoria scales, QoL, suicidality, body image, and surgical outcomes are treated as interchangeable positive signals.
- **No effect-size synthesis.** Cornell never asks how large the effects are or whether they exceed minimum clinically important differences.
- **No sensitivity analyses.** No test of what happens if the weakest studies — those with >40% attrition, no control, or n<30 — are removed.
- **Asymmetric evidentiary standards.** Benefits are counted when self-report outcomes move in a positive direction. Harms are discounted unless a study explicitly concludes transition causes “overall harm.” Harms can appear in bone density, fertility, surgical complications, persistent below-population QoL, or psychiatric morbidity without any study concluding “overall harm.”
- **Temporally frozen.** Locked to 1991–2017. Never updated. Continues to be cited as if it reflects the current evidence state.
- **Summary–body mismatch.** Opening summary: “robust international consensus.” Finding 7: “it is difficult to conduct prospective studies or randomized control trials.” The headline contradicts the methodology. Downstream actors cite the headline.

### The Lindqvist Case

Cornell codes Lindqvist et al. (2017) — a prospective cohort of 190 transgender women at Karolinska, 5-year follow-up — as mixed/null. Correctly. But it illustrates the broader inflation problem.

Lindqvist showed transgender women scored lower than the general population on most SF-36 QoL domains throughout the follow-up period; gains did not persist at 5 years; long-term trajectory was consistent with, not better than, the general population’s age-related decline. The study’s own conclusion: “transgender women generally have a lower QoL compared to the general population.”

A substantial number of the Cornell-positive studies have sample sizes below 30, follow-up periods under 12 months, or no comparator condition of any kind. They count identically to Lindqvist in the directional tally.

That is not a consensus. It is an artifact of the coding scheme.

### The Dhejne Omission

Dhejne et al. (2011) — a population-based matched cohort of all 324 sex-reassigned persons in Sweden, 1973–2003, controls matched 10:1, 30-year follow-up — does not appear in Cornell’s 55-study set despite falling within the 1991–2017 window.

Findings: sex-reassigned persons had considerably higher risks for mortality (aHR 2.8), suicide attempts (aHR 4.9), and psychiatric inpatient care (aHR 2.8) than controls. The authors concluded that “sex reassignment, although alleviating gender dysphoria, may not suffice as treatment for transsexualism.”

Cornell may have excluded it on scope grounds — the study’s primary framing was mortality and morbidity rather than “well-being” as an explicit endpoint. That rationale is not stated. More importantly, it does not hold: psychiatric morbidity and long-term mortality are constitutive of well-being. Excluding the most methodologically rigorous long-term controlled outcome data on those grounds — whether intentional or not — is a consequential methodological choice that substantially affects the apparent consensus.

### Youth vs. Adult: Two Separate Arguments

Two distinct critiques apply here and should not be conflated.

First: the Cass Review, NICE systematic reviews, SBU, and PALKO apply specifically to the *youth* evidence base. Their “very low certainty” findings are directly about the pediatric literature.

Second: the adult clinical follow-up evidence carries its own Cornell-level methodological problems *independently of Cass* — the direction-of-finding coding, loss-to-follow-up, publication bias, outcome heterogeneity, and absence of the decisive test apply to the adult literature as well.

The pipeline’s export of adult findings into youth policy without flagging the level-of-analysis error compounds both problems.

> **Construct validity verdict: C/D border.** Useful for a narrower claim; invalid for the strong claim.
> **Internal validity verdict: D — Suspect.**
> **Citation network verdict: Premise-laundering hub.**

