## Document Three: The Medical Organization Statements Aggregator

The A4TE / transequality.org medical organization statements page presents AMA, AAP, APA, and WPATH endorsements as a third independent evidence source.

It is not independent. Professional association statements are interpretations of the literature. When multiple organizations rely on the same low-certainty studies or the same summary document, their agreement does not multiply the evidence. **It multiplies the citation count.**

The AAP’s 2018 policy statement (Rafferty, 2018) — the anchor of the institutional consensus — rests on a short narrative review. A 2025 peer-reviewed analysis in *Archives of Sexual Behavior* (McDeavitt et al., PMC12011888) found that cited references have been documented as misrepresenting the studies they cite, with Cantor (2020) finding the statement’s references “repeatedly said the very opposite of what AAP attributed to them.” The same paper notes: “The AAP has not acknowledged (as of January 2025) any of the systematic evidence reviews” — meaning Cass, NICE, SBU, and PALKO.

Internally: Resolution 27 (2022), submitted by five AAP members, called for “a rigorous systematic review of evidence and policy update.” The AAP changed procedural rules that year; Resolution 27 was the only resolution affected and did not advance. The AAP Board reaffirmed the 2018 statement in August 2023 while simultaneously authorizing a systematic review — a sequencing Dr. Gordon Guyatt, credited as a developer of evidence-based medicine, described to the *New York Times* as “very clearly putting the cart before the horse,” predicting the forthcoming review would “most likely find low-quality evidence.”

The mechanism: advocacy organizations cite institutional endorsements as evidence; institutional endorsements were produced by citing the same advocacy-adjacent literature; the statements are then cited in policy contexts as independent clinical judgment. That is premise laundering at institutional scale.

> **Verdict: Citation-laundered premise.** Endorsements built on the same evidence base are not independent corroboration.

