## The Failure Mode

The formal list:

**Proxy substitution** — self-reported satisfaction in filtered clinical samples substituted for demonstrated population-level outcomes.

**Level-of-analysis error** — adult clinical findings exported to youth policy; treatment-completer findings exported to access policy for all who might seek treatment.

**Publication bias unaddressed** — absence of contrary findings treated as evidence of safety.

**Loss-to-follow-up ignored** — the systematic absence of dissatisfied, harmed, and detransitioned patients is not incorporated into the summary.

**Hub laundering** — Cornell’s “robust consensus” summary travels without the underlying studies’ caveats.

**Institutional laundering** — organizational statements built on the same base cited as independent corroboration.

**Ratchet** — the pipeline continued operating and expanding after contrary quality-weighted reassessments were available.

### Responses to Common Objections

**“But major medical organizations endorse gender-affirming care.”** The AMA cites AAP; AAP cites the same clinical follow-up cluster; the aggregator presents this chain as independent convergence. Endorsement by multiple organizations that relied on the same low-certainty base does not constitute independent evidence quality. It constitutes institutional amplification.

**“The Cass Review is politically motivated or methodologically flawed.”** Commissioned by NHS England. Led by a former president of the Royal College of Paediatrics and Child Health. Applied explicit GRADE-style quality weighting that Cornell lacked. Reached conclusions consistent with independent health technology bodies in Sweden and Finland — countries with very different political contexts from the UK.

**“The positive studies are still real findings.”** Many are. The claim is not that every positive finding is false. The claim is that a directional vote count from heterogeneous uncontrolled studies does not constitute quality-weighted consensus adequate for the policy uses to which it has been put.

