## What the Evidence Actually Shows

### The Post-2017 Quality-Weighted Reassessments

**Cass Review (2024)** — NHS England. The evidence base for puberty blockers and hormone therapy in youth is “remarkably weak.” By GRADE standards: “very low certainty” for most claimed outcomes. Same literature as Cornell, different quality filter, different conclusion.

**NICE systematic reviews (2020)** — NHS England. Available evidence for puberty blockers and gender-affirming hormones in young people: “very low certainty.”

**SBU (2022)** — Swedish Agency for Health Technology Assessment. Evidence quality for gender-affirming medical treatment in minors: insufficient. Risks including bone density loss, cardiovascular effects, and fertility uncertainty inadequately characterized. Sweden restricted treatments for minors to research settings.

**PALKO/COHERE (2020, updated 2023)** — Finnish Council for Choices in Health Care. Parallel conclusions. Pediatric gender medicine restricted to research protocols.

These reviews do not establish that gender transition causes harm. They establish that the result of quality-weighted methodology applied to this evidence base is “very low certainty” — not “robust consensus.”

### The Ratchet

NICE: 2020. SBU and PALKO: 2022. Cass interim: 2022. Cass final: April 2024.

HRC document updated: **January 2025.** Does not mention Cass. Does not mention NICE. Does not mention Sweden or Finland.

AAP non-acknowledgment of any systematic evidence review: documented by peer-reviewed citation analysis, **also as of January 2025.**

The pipeline’s institutional nodes — advocacy fact sheets, position statements, legal citations — have no built-in mechanisms for downgrading claims when the underlying evidence is reassessed at higher quality standards. The January 2025 HRC update was an active editorial decision during a scheduled update cycle, nine months after the final Cass Report. That choice is documented and specific.

-----

## The Decisive Test

The decisive test for the strong policy claim — that gender transition reliably improves well-being across the range of people who seek it, in sufficient magnitude and certainty to support population-level clinical guidelines — would require:

A pre-registered, adequately powered prospective study following a representative sample of people presenting with gender dysphoria — including those who received and those who did not receive medical intervention — with a matched comparator group, measuring objective and self-reported outcomes across health domains at minimum five and ten years, with independent replication by researchers not connected to the institutional networks that produced the current literature.

That study has not been conducted. Cornell’s Finding 7 acknowledges this and characterizes it as difficult. What Finding 7 does not say is that the absence of the decisive test means the strong policy claim is not established. The Cass Review makes this point directly: clinical confidence in gender-affirming care for youth expanded beyond what the evidence warranted, in part because the field treated the difficulty of rigorous research as a reason to proceed on weaker evidence rather than as a reason for epistemic humility.

-----

## Conclusion

Three documents. One evidentiary base. Cited three times as independent corroboration.

The Cornell document exports a “robust international consensus” summary from a directional vote count that does not weight evidence quality, magnitude, durability, attribution, or population representativeness. The others are an advocacy fact sheet and an aggregator of institutional endorsements produced by citing the same literature.

The narrowest defensible claim the evidence supports: most patients in clinical follow-up samples who completed gender transition and remained in clinical contact reported positive outcomes on self-report measures. Real finding. Real implications. Not settled science adequate for population-level guidelines, clinical mandates for minors, or the foreclosure of further inquiry.

The post-2017 quality-weighted reassessments reached substantially different conclusions about evidence certainty. The pipeline kept running. The January 2025 dates — HRC update, AAP non-acknowledgment — document the ratchet in operation at both the advocacy and institutional levels.

A direction-of-finding consensus is not a GRADE-quality consensus. Institutional repetition cannot convert low-certainty evidence into settled science.

The gap between what the evidence shows and how it has been deployed is the paper.

-----

*One concrete instance of the pipeline in deployment: a February 2026 formal regulatory comment to HHS by the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation — submitted in opposition to a proposed rule restricting Medicaid coverage of gender-affirming care for minors — cites the Cornell document directly, reproducing the “93% of 55 studies” figure as counter-evidence to an HHS review questioning the evidence base. Cornell is cited without qualification or methodological caveat. This is the mechanism operating as described: a directional vote count deployed as quality-equivalent rebuttal to a federal agency’s evidence reassessment.*

